
2
00:00:55,012 --> 00:00:57,378
Ah, there it is. My house.

3
00:00:58,282 --> 00:01:01,683
And good old Cleveland Street. How could I ever forget it?

4
00:01:02,352 --> 00:01:05,253
And there I am, with that dumb round face and...

5
00:01:05,322 --> 00:01:07,153
that stupid stocking cap.

6
00:01:07,991 --> 00:01:10,960
But no matter. Christmas was on its way.

7
00:01:11,261 --> 00:01:14,059
Lovely, glorious, beautiful Christmas...

8
00:01:14,398 --> 00:01:16,992
around which the entire kid year revolved.

9
00:01:40,825 --> 00:01:44,625
Downtown Hohman was prepared for its yearly bacchanalia of...

10
00:01:44,762 --> 00:01:47,356
peace on earth and good will to men.

11
00:02:37,316 --> 00:02:41,013
Higbees' corner window was traditionally a high-water mark...

12
00:02:41,087 --> 00:02:43,078
of the pre-Christmas season.

13
00:02:44,357 --> 00:02:48,657
First nighters, packed earmuff to earmuff, jostled in wonderment...

14
00:02:49,195 --> 00:02:52,562
before a golden tinkling display...

15
00:02:52,899 --> 00:02:56,027
of mechanized, electronic joy.

16
00:03:40,614 --> 00:03:42,411
Wow, there it is.

17
00:03:43,484 --> 00:03:45,918
The holy grail of Christmas gifts.

18
00:03:45,986 --> 00:03:48,887
The Red Ryder 200-shot range model...

19
00:03:48,957 --> 00:03:50,117
air rifle.

20
00:03:51,026 --> 00:03:52,994
And there he is.

21
00:03:53,495 --> 00:03:54,985
Red Ryder himself.

22
00:03:55,430 --> 00:03:59,730
In his hand was the knurled stock of as coolly deadly-looking...

23
00:03:59,801 --> 00:04:03,794
a piece of weaponry as ever I had laid eyes on.

24
00:04:08,510 --> 00:04:12,503
For weeks, I had been scheming to get my mitts on one of these...

25
00:04:12,614 --> 00:04:15,310
fearsome blue-steel beauties.

26
00:04:15,517 --> 00:04:19,749
My fevered brain seethed with the effort of trying to come up with...

27
00:04:19,821 --> 00:04:23,689
the infinitely subtle devices necessary to implant...

28
00:04:23,760 --> 00:04:26,957
the Red Ryder range model air rifle indelibly...

29
00:04:27,263 --> 00:04:29,629
into my parents' subconscious.

30
00:04:29,899 --> 00:04:30,866
Ralphie!

31
00:04:31,401 --> 00:04:32,368
Randy!

32
00:04:32,535 --> 00:04:34,366
Down here in two minutes!

33
00:04:34,771 --> 00:04:36,739
And I mean two minutes!

34
00:04:36,806 --> 00:04:39,274
Come on, Ralphie. I got here first!

35
00:04:45,548 --> 00:04:46,913
Cut it out.

36
00:05:12,676 --> 00:05:15,907
My mother, grabbing for her copy of Look magazine...

37
00:05:16,313 --> 00:05:20,613
would find herself cleverly trapped into reading a Red Ryder sales pitch.

38
00:05:23,454 --> 00:05:25,854
They traded Bullfrog. I don't believe it.

39
00:05:26,490 --> 00:05:27,650
What's that?

40
00:05:28,158 --> 00:05:30,956
Well, for Christ's sake, the Sox traded Bullfrog...

41
00:05:31,028 --> 00:05:33,155
the only player they've got, for Shottenhoffer.

42
00:05:33,298 --> 00:05:35,858
"Four Eyes" Shottenhoffer, a utility infielder.

43
00:05:36,100 --> 00:05:39,092
Got a whole goddamned team of utility infielders.

44
00:05:39,170 --> 00:05:40,569
That's nice.

45
00:05:40,738 --> 00:05:42,638
Ralphie, on the double!

46
00:05:44,275 --> 00:05:46,505
Did you hear about this guy who swallowed a yo-yo?

47
00:05:46,611 --> 00:05:47,873
Swallowed a yo-yo?

48
00:05:47,873 --> 00:05:49,273
On a bet.

49
00:05:49,347 --> 00:05:51,872
Some clodhopper down in Griffith, Indiana.

50
00:05:53,218 --> 00:05:55,948
They write the silliest things in the newspapers.

51
00:05:56,354 --> 00:05:58,982
What do you mean, silly? I mean that's real news.

52
00:05:59,090 --> 00:06:01,183
That's not like that politics slop.

53
00:06:02,293 --> 00:06:06,957
What is the name of the Lone Ranger's nephew's horse?

54
00:06:07,666 --> 00:06:09,463
Victor. His name is Victor.

55
00:06:09,869 --> 00:06:11,361
How the hell did you know that?

56
00:06:11,361 --> 00:06:12,861
Everybody knows that.

57
00:06:14,540 --> 00:06:17,168
That's another one of your silly puzzles?

58
00:06:17,376 --> 00:06:19,708
Yeah, it's another one of our silly puzzles.

59
00:06:19,778 --> 00:06:23,145
Could be worth $50,000.

60
00:06:24,283 --> 00:06:26,046
What kind is it this time?

61
00:06:26,485 --> 00:06:29,613
Name the great characters in American literature.

62
00:06:30,389 --> 00:06:33,847
Victor? The Lone Ranger's nephew's horse?

63
00:06:34,093 --> 00:06:37,358
Meanwhile, I struggled for exactly the right BB gun hint.

64
00:06:37,429 --> 00:06:38,862
It had to be firm, but subtle.

65
00:06:39,098 --> 00:06:42,124
Flick says he saw some grizzly bears near Pulaski's candy store.

66
00:06:48,041 --> 00:06:51,875
They looked at me as if I had lobsters crawling out of my ears.

67
00:06:52,946 --> 00:06:56,712
I could tell that I was in imminent danger of over-playing my hand.

68
00:06:57,551 --> 00:06:59,451
Casually, I switched tactics.

69
00:07:00,120 --> 00:07:01,212
Hey, Dad!

70
00:07:02,522 --> 00:07:05,787
I'll bet you'll never guess what I got you for Christmas.

71
00:07:07,327 --> 00:07:08,658
A new furnace.

72
00:07:10,497 --> 00:07:12,055
That's a good one, Dad.

73
00:07:13,466 --> 00:07:16,697
My old man was one of the most feared furnace-fighters...

74
00:07:16,771 --> 00:07:18,534
in northern Indiana.

75
00:07:18,906 --> 00:07:21,636
Hurry up, you're going to be late for school.

76
00:07:21,943 --> 00:07:24,309
Yeah. I'm running late already.

77
00:07:24,579 --> 00:07:26,103
Round one was over.

78
00:07:26,981 --> 00:07:28,107
Parents, one.

79
00:07:28,249 --> 00:07:29,307
Kids, zip.

80
00:07:30,851 --> 00:07:33,718
I could feel the Christmas noose beginning to tighten.

81
00:07:34,055 --> 00:07:37,024
Maybe what happened next was inevitable.

82
00:07:37,091 --> 00:07:39,685
Ralphie, what would you like for Christmas?

83
00:07:39,827 --> 00:07:42,022
Horrified, I heard myself blurt it out.

84
00:07:42,129 --> 00:07:46,156
I want an official Red Ryder carbine action 200-shot range model air rifle.

85
00:07:47,401 --> 00:07:49,335
No. Shoot your eye out.

86
00:07:49,404 --> 00:07:53,170
Oh, no! It was the classic mother-BB gun block.

87
00:07:53,609 --> 00:07:55,133
"You'll shoot your eye out."

88
00:07:55,377 --> 00:07:59,006
That deadly phrase uttered many times before by hundreds...

89
00:07:59,114 --> 00:08:01,082
of mothers was not surmountable...

90
00:08:01,149 --> 00:08:03,174
by any means known to kid-dom.

91
00:08:03,352 --> 00:08:07,152
But such was my mania, my desire for a Red Ryder carbine...

92
00:08:07,255 --> 00:08:10,520
that I immediately began to rebuild the dike.

93
00:08:11,627 --> 00:08:14,721
I was just kidding. Even though Flick is getting one.

94
00:08:15,397 --> 00:08:16,830
I'd just like some Tinkertoys.

95
00:08:16,898 --> 00:08:19,458
I couldn't believe my own ears. Tinkertoys?

96
00:08:19,601 --> 00:08:21,000
She'd never buy it.

97
00:08:21,436 --> 00:08:23,267
BB guns are dangerous.

98
00:08:23,338 --> 00:08:24,930
I don't want anyone shooting his eye out.

99
00:08:30,813 --> 00:08:34,647
Randy, will you eat? There are starving people in China.

100
00:08:44,093 --> 00:08:46,755
Mothers know nothing about creeping marauders...

101
00:08:46,929 --> 00:08:48,920
burrowing through the snow toward the kitchen...

102
00:08:48,998 --> 00:08:52,525
where only you, and you alone, stand between your tiny...

103
00:08:52,702 --> 00:08:55,432
huddled family and insensate evil.

104
00:09:03,313 --> 00:09:06,544
Save us, Ralphie! I just knew those bad guys...

105
00:09:06,617 --> 00:09:09,051
would be coming for us in the end!

106
00:09:09,953 --> 00:09:13,184
Don't worry, Dad. As long as I got OI' Blue...

107
00:09:17,861 --> 00:09:19,294
What've we got here, folks?

108
00:09:19,363 --> 00:09:22,298
Well, we figure it's Black Bart, Ralph.

109
00:09:22,666 --> 00:09:24,930
Well, just me and my trusty old...

110
00:09:25,035 --> 00:09:28,732
Red Ryder carbine-action 200-shot range model air rifle.

111
00:09:29,239 --> 00:09:31,799
Lucky I've got a compass in the stock.

112
00:09:32,042 --> 00:09:34,272
Well, I think I better have a look here.

113
00:09:48,226 --> 00:09:49,386
Oh, no!

114
00:09:49,861 --> 00:09:52,159
It's OI' Blue!

115
00:09:52,464 --> 00:09:53,863
Oh, no!

116
00:09:54,666 --> 00:09:56,258
Cheese it, boys!

117
00:10:08,347 --> 00:10:12,044
There's another one! He's a dead-eye, ain't he?

118
00:10:19,258 --> 00:10:20,816
Okay, Ralphie!

119
00:10:20,893 --> 00:10:23,987
You win this time, but we'll be back!

120
00:10:29,001 --> 00:10:30,400
Adi¨®s, Bart.

121
00:10:31,103 --> 00:10:34,766
But if you do come back, you'll be pushing up daisies!

122
00:10:39,712 --> 00:10:41,179
And don't you forget it!

123
00:10:41,247 --> 00:10:42,805
Well, son, you saved us!

124
00:10:42,883 --> 00:10:45,909
We were goners for sure! And you saved us!

125
00:10:54,394 --> 00:10:55,759
Oldsmobile!

126
00:10:56,163 --> 00:10:57,687
A pile of junk!

127
00:10:58,932 --> 00:11:01,127
That goddamned Olds is froze up again!

128
00:11:01,201 --> 00:11:06,002
Some men are Baptists, others Catholics. My father was an Oldsmobile man.

129
00:11:06,306 --> 00:11:10,367
That son of a bitch would freeze up in the middle of summer on the Equator!

130
00:11:10,744 --> 00:11:12,106
Little pitchers...

131
00:11:12,106 --> 00:11:13,406
Hold it!

132
00:11:26,794 --> 00:11:28,318
It's a clinker!

133
00:11:30,131 --> 00:11:32,258
That blasted, stupid furnace.

134
00:11:32,333 --> 00:11:33,664
Dadgummit!

135
00:11:38,906 --> 00:11:40,396
Damn skates!

136
00:11:43,311 --> 00:11:45,506
For Christ's sake, open up the damper, will you?

137
00:11:45,580 --> 00:11:48,276
Who the hell turned it all the way down again?

138
00:11:49,250 --> 00:11:50,274
Blasted!

139
00:11:59,928 --> 00:12:04,661
In the heat of battle, my father wove a tapestry of obscenity...

140
00:12:04,900 --> 00:12:09,269
that as far as we know is still hanging in space over Lake Michigan.

141
00:12:20,682 --> 00:12:23,082
Preparing to go to school was like getting ready...

142
00:12:23,151 --> 00:12:25,619
for extended deep-sea diving.

143
00:12:45,108 --> 00:12:47,310
Come on, Mom, we're going to be late!

144
00:12:47,310 --> 00:12:49,010
Just wait, Ralph!

145
00:12:50,246 --> 00:12:52,806
My kid brother looked like a tick about to pop.

146
00:12:52,882 --> 00:12:53,678
What?

147
00:12:54,884 --> 00:12:55,714
What is it?

148
00:12:56,686 --> 00:12:58,347
What is it?

149
00:13:02,326 --> 00:13:03,625
What is it?

150
00:13:03,625 --> 00:13:05,625
I can't put my arms down!

151
00:13:17,207 --> 00:13:19,767
Well, put your arms down when you get to school.

152
00:13:49,741 --> 00:13:51,231
Hey, Flick! Wait up.

153
00:13:51,376 --> 00:13:52,604
Wait up!

154
00:13:53,311 --> 00:13:54,369
So what are you doing?

155
00:13:54,612 --> 00:13:57,046
What does it look like I'm doing? Picking goobers?

156
00:13:57,282 --> 00:14:00,683
Hey, listen, smart ass. I asked my old man about sticking...

157
00:14:00,752 --> 00:14:03,152
your tongue to metal light poles in winter...

158
00:14:03,221 --> 00:14:06,622
and he says it will freeze right to the pole just like I told you.

159
00:14:06,858 --> 00:14:07,882
Baloney.

160
00:14:07,959 --> 00:14:09,927
What would your old man know about anything?

161
00:14:09,996 --> 00:14:12,294
He knows because he once saw a guy stick his tongue...

162
00:14:12,365 --> 00:14:15,960
to a railroad track on a bet and the fire department had to come...

163
00:14:16,035 --> 00:14:19,903
to get the guy's tongue off the track because he couldn't get it off.

164
00:14:19,972 --> 00:14:21,735
Come on, guys, wait up!

165
00:14:21,807 --> 00:14:23,297
Come on, guys!

166
00:14:23,776 --> 00:14:26,006
Come on, guys, wait up!

167
00:14:31,250 --> 00:14:32,649
I can't get up!

168
00:14:33,953 --> 00:14:35,716
I can't get up!

169
00:14:35,788 --> 00:14:36,720
Help!

170
00:14:38,157 --> 00:14:40,421
I can't get out! Help me!

171
00:14:41,827 --> 00:14:43,488
Come on, Flick, wait up for me.

172
00:14:43,597 --> 00:14:45,394
I can't get up!

173
00:14:48,869 --> 00:14:49,665
Come on.

174
00:14:49,736 --> 00:14:52,068
Get up. Sit up. Come on.

175
00:14:53,907 --> 00:14:55,340
You're okay. Come on, let's go.

176
00:14:55,409 --> 00:14:56,740
Come on, you're all right!

177
00:15:05,986 --> 00:15:06,953
Miss Shields!

178
00:15:07,954 --> 00:15:09,012
All right, everyone...

179
00:15:09,089 --> 00:15:10,750
take your seats, please.

180
00:15:18,800 --> 00:15:20,597
Good morning, class.

181
00:15:20,668 --> 00:15:24,001
Good morning, Miss Shields.

182
00:15:58,841 --> 00:16:01,241
Open your books to Page 32.

183
00:16:01,310 --> 00:16:04,177
And as you'll remember, Silas Marner...

184
00:16:14,656 --> 00:16:17,284
You're full of beans and so's your old man.

185
00:16:18,460 --> 00:16:19,690
Says who?

186
00:16:19,690 --> 00:16:20,690
Says me.

187
00:16:20,762 --> 00:16:22,662
Well, I double-dare you.

188
00:16:22,731 --> 00:16:25,325
The exact exchange and nuance...

189
00:16:25,467 --> 00:16:28,925
of phrase in this ritual is very important.

190
00:16:29,172 --> 00:16:31,732
Are you kidding? Stick my tongue to that stupid pole?

191
00:16:31,841 --> 00:16:32,808
That's dumb.

192
00:16:32,876 --> 00:16:34,844
That's 'cause you know it will stick!

193
00:16:34,944 --> 00:16:36,536
You're full of it.

194
00:16:37,080 --> 00:16:39,207
Well, I double dog-dare you!

195
00:16:39,749 --> 00:16:42,980
Now it was serious. A double dog-dare.

196
00:16:43,486 --> 00:16:45,647
What else was left but a "triple-dare you"?

197
00:16:45,755 --> 00:16:48,280
And finally, the coup de grace of all dares...

198
00:16:48,358 --> 00:16:50,758
the sinister triple dog-dare!

199
00:16:51,361 --> 00:16:53,921
I triple dog-dare you!

200
00:16:54,931 --> 00:16:57,399
Schwartz created a slight breach of etiquette...

201
00:16:57,500 --> 00:17:01,129
by skipping the triple-dare and going right for the throat.

202
00:17:01,204 --> 00:17:02,535
All right, all right.

203
00:17:12,249 --> 00:17:14,082
Go on, smart ass, and do it!

204
00:17:14,082 --> 00:17:15,582
I'm going!

205
00:17:16,253 --> 00:17:20,314
Flick's spine stiffened, his lips curled in a defiant sneer.

206
00:17:20,858 --> 00:17:22,826
There was no going back now.

207
00:17:25,863 --> 00:17:27,455
This is nothing.

208
00:17:31,835 --> 00:17:33,462
Stuck? Stuck!

209
00:17:33,537 --> 00:17:35,630
Stuck! Stuck!

210
00:17:41,546 --> 00:17:42,638
Jeez!

211
00:17:42,781 --> 00:17:44,214
It really works!

212
00:17:44,282 --> 00:17:45,715
Look at him!

213
00:17:56,061 --> 00:17:57,460
Ralphie, come back!

214
00:17:57,529 --> 00:17:59,429
Come back! Don't leave me! Come back!

215
00:17:59,429 --> 00:18:00,930
But the bell rang!

216
00:18:01,066 --> 00:18:02,758
What are we going to do?

217
00:18:02,758 --> 00:18:04,558
I don't know! The bell rang!

218
00:18:14,747 --> 00:18:16,009
Where's Flick?

219
00:18:17,750 --> 00:18:19,081
Has anyone seen Flick?

220
00:18:19,252 --> 00:18:20,981
Flick? Flick who?

221
00:18:21,053 --> 00:18:23,180
He was at recess, wasn't he?

222
00:18:24,824 --> 00:18:27,315
Ralphie, do you know where Flick is?

223
00:18:32,965 --> 00:18:36,366
I said has anyone seen Flick?

224
00:18:38,738 --> 00:18:40,365
Yes, Esther Jane?

225
00:18:46,446 --> 00:18:48,038
Oh, my God!

226
00:19:08,902 --> 00:19:11,393
Holy cow, it's the fire department!

227
00:19:18,512 --> 00:19:20,241
Wow, it's the cops!

228
00:20:12,735 --> 00:20:16,762
Now, I know that some of you put Flick up to this.

229
00:20:19,475 --> 00:20:22,035
But, he has refused to say who.

230
00:20:24,646 --> 00:20:27,274
But those who did it know their blame.

231
00:20:29,419 --> 00:20:32,479
And I'm sure the guilt you feel...

232
00:20:32,722 --> 00:20:36,681
is far worse than any punishment you might receive.

233
00:20:40,997 --> 00:20:43,124
Now, don't you feel terrible?

234
00:20:44,234 --> 00:20:47,067
Don't you feel remorse for what you have done?

235
00:20:49,472 --> 00:20:52,236
That's all I'm going to say about poor Flick.

236
00:20:55,278 --> 00:20:58,736
Adults love to say things like that. But kids know better.

237
00:20:58,815 --> 00:21:02,649
We knew darn well it was always better not to get caught.

238
00:21:02,752 --> 00:21:06,017
Now, boys and girls, I'm going to give you an assignment.

239
00:21:07,224 --> 00:21:08,919
I want you to write...

240
00:21:09,994 --> 00:21:11,188
a theme.

241
00:21:14,799 --> 00:21:17,097
"What I want for Christmas."

242
00:21:18,469 --> 00:21:19,959
The clouds lifted.

243
00:21:20,504 --> 00:21:22,904
And I want it handed in tomorrow morning...

244
00:21:22,973 --> 00:21:26,067
I saw a faint gleam of light at the other end of...

245
00:21:26,143 --> 00:21:28,008
the black cave of doom.

246
00:21:28,078 --> 00:21:32,105
I knew that when Miss Shields read my magnificent, eloquent theme...

247
00:21:32,183 --> 00:21:34,981
that she would sympathize with my plight...

248
00:21:35,052 --> 00:21:38,249
and everything would work out, somehow.

249
00:21:53,605 --> 00:21:56,073
Boy, did you see how it stuck?

250
00:21:56,641 --> 00:21:58,072
Did it hurt, Flick?

251
00:21:58,072 --> 00:21:59,872
No. I never felt a thing.

252
00:21:59,945 --> 00:22:01,372
It just caught me off-guard.

253
00:22:01,446 --> 00:22:02,874
You sure were bawling.

254
00:22:02,874 --> 00:22:04,274
I never bawled!

255
00:22:04,416 --> 00:22:05,883
Baloney.

256
00:22:19,031 --> 00:22:20,589
Scut Farkus!

257
00:22:21,200 --> 00:22:24,795
Scut Farkus! What a rotten name. We were trapped.

258
00:22:24,871 --> 00:22:27,772
There he stood, between us and the alley.

259
00:22:27,840 --> 00:22:30,900
Scut Farkus, staring out at us with his yellow eyes.

260
00:22:31,244 --> 00:22:34,475
He had yellow eyes! So help me God, yellow eyes.

261
00:22:49,997 --> 00:22:52,693
Grover Dill, Farkus' crummy little toady.

262
00:22:52,766 --> 00:22:54,256
Mean. Rotten.

